TY  - JOUR
T1  - On the Mathematical Theory of Schedules
AU  - Mayhugh, J. O.
Y1  - 1964/11/01
PY  - 1964
DA  - 1964/11/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.11.2.289
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.11.2.289
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 289
EP  - 307
VL  - 11
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The elapsed time to complete a scheduled task is expressed as a function of the completion times of the component tasks and the path matrix of the scheddule graph. The schedule function is interpreted geometrically as a polyhedron. If the scheduled activities have random completion times, the probability distribution of the time to complete the entire task is found by integrating over the contours of the polyhedron. Composite schedule functions are represented by algebraic formulae which are applicable in both the probabilistic and non-probabilistic cases. A method for joint control of cost and schedule is presented.
AB  - The elapsed time to complete a scheduled task is expressed as a function of the completion times of the component tasks and the path matrix of the scheddule graph. The schedule function is interpreted geometrically as a polyhedron. If the scheduled activities have random completion times, the probability distribution of the time to complete the entire task is found by integrating over the contours of the polyhedron. Composite schedule functions are represented by algebraic formulae which are applicable in both the probabilistic and non-probabilistic cases. A method for joint control of cost and schedule is presented.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.11.2.289
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.11.2.289
Y2  - 2024/03/27
